DDoS Attack Trends in 2022

January 10, 2023
443

We observe the greatest upsurge in DDoS attacks in recorded history. According to our data, the number of attacks already increased by 20% in the second half of 2022 compared to its first half. We have compiled analytics into a comprehensive report, and are now ready to tell you how the landscape of DDoS attacks changed in 2022.

General Trends

Ongoing geopolitical events made the number of attacks on Russian websites increase by 700%, compared to 2021. The primary targets were websites related to the media, government, and financial services. 

1,255,573 is the total number of DDoS attacks detected and successfully mitigated by DDoS-Guard in 2022.

The average daily number of DDoS attacks increased by 10 times, and the number of attacks per hour increased by 11 times. The most intense months were March and August.

There is an insignificant correlation between the number of attacks and days of the week. But as for the working hours, we observed the most intensive malicious activity from 9 am to 8 pm. It makes sense, since it’s the perfect time to do the most damage, especially when the primary targets are corporate platforms, mass media, governmental and financial companies.

Increased Frequency of the Attacks 

The duration of DDoS attacks has decreased, in comparison to 2021. Nevertheless, the frequency has increased by 3-4 times. The reason behind that change is technical: it is too expensive to use powerful botnets to attack Russian websites massively. Instead, hackers have formed new communities to share the instructions on how to generate malicious traffic and orchestrate DDoS attacks. Custom botnets are mostly capable of massive-scale attacks, but not of the prolonged ones.

In 2022, the vast majority of DDoS attacks lasted up to 20 minutes, and a significant number of them lasted from 20 minutes to 1 hour. Attacks lasting 24 hours or longer comprise less than 1% of the total number of incidents.

It has become much easier to organize the DDoS attack. The participant no longer needs to install special software to make their device a part of an attacking botnet. A brand new category of websites has been launched specifically for organizing DDoS attacks. A user can only visit a certain webpage to become a gear in an immense cybercrime machine.

The general trend, as it comes clear from the data, is to do as many “micro-bites” as possible for as many sites as possible.

Hacktivism

The word of the year. The cyberattack landscape has changed dramatically with certain geopolitical events in 2022. At the beginning of the year, we still observed the former trend of long-term attacks, but the situation turned out to be completely different in late February. 
Before 2022, the most common motivation for DDoS attacks was professional competition for websites in taking top positions in search results. Attacks were seasonal and directly correlated to specific dates like national holidays, when people usually spend their time and money on online-shopping. Hackers blackmailed the website owners during peak visits and demanded a ransom to stop the attack. Site owners had to make a tough choice between paying with no guarantee, or watching their customers leave for competitors, because the site was unavailable.

The fundamental motivation for DDoS attacks in 2022 was hacktivism — biased cybercrimes that are committed to supporting certain political ideas. Hacktivists used every known method and tool in their campaigns. At first, the attack patterns seemed chaotic, but in the spring we noticed a more professional approach. Hacktivists gathered into ideological groups to orchestrate massive cyber attacks on the Russian Internet segment.

The year 2022 has become a major stress test for us all since its beginning. We had to regroup and implement new monitoring, analysis, and scrubbing tools urgently. Until the beginning of August, we were in emergency mode of working. The vector of attacks was constantly changing, with the number of attacking devices growing higher and higher. The information background has become the defining factor, shaping the specifics of attacks and potential targets. We expect this trend to remain for a few months ahead.

Dmitriy Nikonov, expert in website protection, DDoS-Guard

Emphasis on Application Layer Attacks

We observed an over 600% increase in the number of DDoS attacks in the first half of 2022. Most of them were application layer attacks (L7, according to the OSI model). Meanwhile, the dynamics of attacks have been transforming as the time went, and seasons changed.

At the very beginning of the year, we registered mostly heterogeneous, specific attacks. After the hacktivists coordinated into groups, their methods became more structured and typical, and the attacks turned out more or less predictable, despite their growing number. 
Another turning point was at the beginning of autumn. The attack patterns remained the same, but the behavior of the attackers changed noticeably. So they prepared more carefully by improving coordination, evaluating potential targets, and selecting the most vulnerable websites.

We also found out that the route of malicious requests during a modernized attack can transform, switching between vulnerable website components: from the root section — to authorization forms — to tools for interacting with external applications (API).

Since the API traffic is of automated nature and mostly legitimate, it needs a special approach to analyze and mitigate DDoS attacks. So we developed a new feature for this purpose — Protection Rules, so our customers now can fine-tune filters for incoming traffic.

New Primary Targets

Until the beginning of 2022, a majority of attacks targeted Arts & Entertainment websites. That online category saw much more malicious traffic than business portals, telecom and educational platforms, which took the top-attacked badge before. All of them are still at risk, and the dynamics of attacks have multiplied. For example, Arts & Entertainment websites experienced 6 times more attacks — 44,000 compared to 7,700 in 2021.

However, the scene got slightly different after February. Hacktivists determined the mass media their primary target. Regardless of its popularity, any website posting news articles would become a bullseye. This is how they achieved the status of the most attacked category in 2022. The number of DDoS attacks on media portals increased by a record-breaking 76 times (51,842 incidents compared to 670 in 2021). Government-related websites were also constantly under attack, with the number of incidents increased by 55 times (20,766 compared to 370). The websites of banks and financial organizations were attacked 20 times more often than in 2021 (27,600 incidents compared to 1,318).

Micro DDoS Attacks Against Media Sites

In 2022, we frequently encountered multiple minor attacks on small sites, or on each IP throughout the subnet. Malefactors usually followed such a scheme to damage regional media websites. 

This kind of attack may bring a light load to a particular media, ranging from 500 to 2,000 RPS. However, when you have several websites using the same IP address targeted, the total flow gets noticeable. Attackers might consider minor attacks harder to mitigate and, therefore, more efficient. But the DDoS-Guard scrubbing system recognizes such attacks and promptly handles them.

There were some curious cases: for example, the site of one minor project had been receiving an avalanche of malicious requests for about 70 days in a row. The DDoS-Guard system mitigated the attack without the customer being affected by it. But for an unprotected site, such an incident would mean network performance degradation or a server failure. With a constant stream of attack traffic, the administrator would only have to place a “maintenance” banner on the site.

Attack Seasonality and Scheduling

In 2022, hacktivists often launched DDoS attacks on certain dates when they could do the most damage. Thus, we detected multiple attacks on financial institutions, advisory and accounting services on the days of quarterly and semiannual reporting.

Attackers similarly targeted local telecom and public utility provider websites on days when users were to submit meter readings and pay bills. They also targeted banks to disrupt payment processing.

Hacktivists actively followed the schedule and monitored the news agenda. As an example, they launched attacks coinciding with Russian holidays, such as Victory Day (May 9) and Independence Day (June 12). Any widely disseminated news involving officials or major corporations resulted in attacks on web resources that posted it.

What to Expect in 2023

Given the geopolitical tensions, the number of incidents is likely to triple by the spring of 2023. However, the overall trend will move from quantity to quality. Constant DDoS attacks are now the norm, which we must accept and for which reliable protection is essential.

If attacks were massive last year, they are now more intelligent and sophisticated in terms of preparation and methods. Successful cybercrimes will inflict far more damage. Hacktivists seem to focus on corporate ecosystem services and applications that are used concurrently by hundreds of companies. Vulnerabilities will undoubtedly serve as an additional targeting factor.

We expect to see an increase in cyberthreats involving rootkits, ransomware, more information leakages as a consequence. Standard types of attacks, such as TCP- and UDP-flood, will still be relevant.

Unprotected resources belonging to previously unpopular sectors may now be of interest to hackers because of their affiliation with the Russian segment of the Internet. Even so, the risk of becoming an accidental victim of an attack also persists. In 2023, every online project is vulnerable to a DDoS attack, whether it is a large corporate platform or a minor website. Such threats can be fatal to the latter category.

See more stats and comparison to 2021 in our  Analytical Report on DDoS Attacks for 2022.
